**Background:**

- MongoDB has added the expressive updates in version 3.6 to update items inside an array using [$\[\]][1] and [$\[itentifier\]][2] operators you can take advantage if you plan to use your existing data model
- However, the data model for your case goes with the third type based [on schema-design patterns for one-to-N models proposed by MongoDB][3]. In particular: One-to-Squillions using parent-referencing

**Data Model:**

 Collection stocks:

    {
       _id: &quot;CZ01&quot;
       stock_provider: &quot;ABC&quot;,
       supplier_id:&quot;SUP1&quot;
     
    }

Collection `product_items:`

    {
        &quot;code&quot;: &quot;&lt;string&gt;&quot;,
        &quot;stock_id&quot;: &quot;CZ01&quot;,
        &quot;price&quot;: &lt;double&gt;,
        &quot;price_lastupdate&quot;: &lt;date&gt;,
        &quot;stock&quot;: &lt;int&gt;,
        &quot;stock_lastupdate&quot;:&lt;date&gt;
    }

**Queries**:

- possible to insert a new products (code + stock_id is unique): Create a compound unique index on `code and stock_id` to maintain uniqueness in product_items collection
- update price_lastupdate only when the price was changed than before: Create a [change stream][4] to watch the updates on the product_items.price to update the value of product.price_lastupdate. [Here is the example][5]:


  
   `const mongo = require(&quot;mongodb&quot;).MongoClient;
     mongo.connect(&quot;mongodb://localhost:27017/?replicaSet=rs0&quot;).then(client =&gt; {
     console.log(&quot;Connected to MongoDB server&quot;);
