So after a frustrating 2 days of time-wasting on this, it turns out the problem is coming from the function of:

    @AfterClass
    public static void afterClass(){
      log.debug(&quot;Stopping containers...&quot;);
      couchbaseContainer.stop();
    }


Simply removing the call to 

    couchbaseContainer.stop();

Solved the problem.

It appears that even though the `afterClass` is stopping the `Couchbase` container, something else is also trying to stop it as can be seen in the stack trace:

    at org.testcontainers.couchbase.CouchbaseContainer.stopCluster(CouchbaseContainer.java:198)
    at org.testcontainers.couchbase.CouchbaseContainer.stop(CouchbaseContainer.java:193)

So actually the solution was to remove the `stop()` from the `afterClass` and let the other thing stop the container.

