The syntax `digits_[DIGITS] = { 0 };` here does not initialise all the elements of `digits_` to `0`. It accesses the *`DIGITS`-th* element (one past the end - this is index out of bounds) and sets it do `0`. This is *undefined behaviour* and a program that exhibits one may behave in any way - expected or unexpected.

The fix is quite easy. The very same syntax (`digits_[DIGITS] = { 0 };`) *can* be used to initialize all the elements to `0`, but it must be used in the *declaration*. So, in order to fix the issue you must:

1. get rid of the above constructor
2. replace `int digits_[DIGITS];` in your **header file** with `int digits_[DIGITS] = {0};`.

*EDIT*:

It appears that you had another bug - in your `operator &gt;&gt;`. The line:
    
    n.digits_[i] = s[s.length() - 1 - i] - &#39;0&#39;;

also invokes *undefined behaviour* unless the `length()` of `s` is exactly `DIGITS`. When you input `00000`, `s.length() == 5`. Now, your `i` range is from `0` to `DIGITS` (`255`). What happens when, let&#39;s say, `i == 100`? The following gets executed:

    n.digits_[100] = s[-96] - &#39;0&#39;;

And this is not what we want. You need to add a guard for that. For example:

    n.digits_[i] = i &lt; s.length() ? s[s.length() - 1 - i] - &#39;0&#39; : 0;

