The reason you are seeing #null for the job is because the entity the DbContext returned you on the final query would have been the instance you initiated and attached to the context.  When you call SaveChanges with your entity, it had an ID of 1, Name of &quot;Jack&quot; and a Job of #null. The tracking told EF only the name had changed, so that is all that went to the DB in the Update statement. 

EF does some slightly dubious stuff behind the scenes, but when you fetch an entity it will return whatever it has in the cache if available before loading an entity from the database. What can be confusing about that is that if you are profiling against the DB you will see a `SELECT` raised against the database, but the entity returned will reflect the last cached state, not the database State.  To refresh the entity you can either:

    _context.Entity(user).Reload();

to reload the entity being tracked. or ...

    _context.Entity(user).EntityState = EntityState.Detached;
    user = _context.Users.Single(x =&gt; x.Id == 1);

... to detach the entity you updated again to force EF to reload when asked or ...

    user = _context.Users.AsNoTracking().Single(x =&gt; x.Id == 1);

... load a fresh untracked reference.

As a general rule, when editing entities you should load the entity, apply the changes, and save rather than the Id + `Attach` trick. Id + `Attach` is a handy hack for delete scenarios or possibly bulk updates, but only within short-lived DbContexts so that these tracked &quot;partial&quot; entities don&#39;t get returned again by other queries.

